#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
cxp — codexpool: make several ChatGPT Pro accounts behave as one Codex login.

A localhost token-injecting proxy. Codex is pointed at it via `chatgpt_base_url`.
For each request the proxy picks an account by LIVE usage, injects that account's
bearer token, and streams the response straight back. It is the SOLE refresher per
account (so single-use rotating refresh tokens are never copied or raced — the bug
that forced constant re-logins), and it rotates accounts only BETWEEN turns: on a
real quota wall or when live usage drops under the spillover threshold.

Design + rationale: ./DESIGN.md and ../analysis/TAXONOMY.md
Protocol constants verified against vendored codex source (login/src/auth/manager.rs)
and the proven codex-usage-probe.

Usage:
  cxp [codex args...]    launch codex through the pool (default)
  cxp proxy              run the proxy in the foreground (normally auto-spawned)
  cxp status             per-account live usage + routing + proxy health
  cxp import             (re)seed the pool from ~/.codex/accounts/*.auth.json
  cxp login [hint]       sign one account into the pool without touching ~/.codex
  cxp auth-log           show recent auth/login events
  cxp quarantine         move pooled ~/.codex credentials aside so cxp owns refresh
  cxp unquarantine       restore files moved by `cxp quarantine`
  cxp stop               stop the shared proxy and clean the port file
  cxp restart            restart the shared proxy
  cxp install-agent      install a launchd agent that keeps the proxy alive
  cxp uninstall-agent    remove the launchd agent
"""
